So the story in the OT where God tells Moses "Ok, these people are bad enough I'm just going to kill them all and make a new nation out of your offspring."&nbsp; Well Moses argues with God and convinces Him to have mercy on the Israelites and give them another chance.&nbsp; I have heard this story explained away many times by well-meaning people who say that God would never commit genocide and that this was just a test for Moses.&nbsp; 

However, not only do we have quite clear evidence that God *would* in fact commit genocide (look at his commands about the canaanites and other heathen nations the israelites fought in later years), but this denies a clear theme that runs throughout the OT and indeed throughout the whole Bible: that the prayers of righteous people DO in fact make a difference with God.&nbsp; This theme gets stated over and over again throughout countless OT and NT stories (if you can't think of any I can give you a few hints), and I don't think it's necessarily wrong to think that possibly if Moses had agreed with God, God would have done just what He said.

So therefore this leads us to an answer to another <a href="http://www.livejournal.com/users/fenrah/82115.html">delima</a>.&nbsp; We do not want God in the OT to be only slightly better than Molech, we want Him to be GOOD and UNCHANGEABLE like He says.&nbsp; But we have genocides or near genocides (oh you are allowed to keep the virgin daughters and marry them and rape them after they have had a month to grieve the family you killed) and things that seem to run counter to the 10 commandments so what do we do?&nbsp; God appears to do things He can do LEGALLY but that are neither just nor merciful.&nbsp; 

And I think the thing we don't recognize here is not that God was only slightly better than Molech but that he was dealing with a people that were only slightly better than Molech.&nbsp; God's wisdom said to wipe them all out and start over again because they were REALLY bad.&nbsp; On the pleas of a truly righteous man God spares them, but He must then deal with them.&nbsp; And unfortunatley He *had* to allow them to do some things (Jesus says divorce was one of them) that were wrong because he couldn't take them from detestable-enough-to-be-worthy-of-genocide-themselves straight to angelic without lots and lots of tiny steps.

Okay so that is not all the answer and there's plenty more to be said on the matter, but that is part of my own personal answer at least.&nbsp; Time for bed now.

